## âœ… Meaning of **O(b^m)**

* **b** = *branching factor*:
  the average number of children each node has.

* **m** = *maximum depth* of the search (or the depth limit, if DFS).

So **O(b^m)** describes how the number of nodes grows **exponentially** with depth.

More depth â†’ exponentially more nodes â†’ more time and memory.

---

## ğŸ“Œ Why O(b^m)?

If each node has **b** children, then:

* Level 0 has 1 node
* Level 1 has b nodes
* Level 2 has bÂ² nodes
* â€¦
* Level m has b^m nodes

Total nodes explored in the worst case â‰ˆ b^m
â¡ï¸ Hence **O(b^m)**.

